column1: Will there be a lethal confrontation between the national military forces and/or law enforcement of Russia and those of a NATO member state resulting in at least three fatalities before 8 November 2022?
column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Security and Conflict']
Passing of time
Only one week left until the end of time period.
to risk open "command authorization" would be too much
Passing of time.
Very unlikely before 8 November. Pity I didn't see this question earlier

One way for Putin to save some face, for a while at least, would be to pull NATO more directly into the war. If NATO is involved he can point to the fact that he has always said this is a larger fight between Russia and the West, which wants to destroy Russia. He doesn't want to get spanked by NATO air power, but he would like to be able to point to something that supports his position. So with four weeks left I'll move up to 8%, matching the crowd.
There are only 4 weeks left on the question. Things are a little hot right now, but indications are Russia does not want NATO drawn into the conflict.
This forecast is the application of a Bayesian update from my initial prediction of 7% back in September.
No new analysis below - Staying the same
stillhappenedbutnotconfirmed@ferryman

Odds just increased given Putin's annexation of partially occupied territory in Ukraine and his multiple threats against the "anglo-saxon" world. I think Putin intends to continue to escalate the conflict and the risk is present.
Only one week remaining.

I think Putin may be reaching the point where he is the one who feels the need to call the bluff of NATO, which has drawn a pretty hard line in the sand (at least based an account of direct backchannel communications between the White House and the Kremline told by National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan yesterday on Meet the Press).
unlikely but accidents happen
Passing of time.
With their current trouble in Ukraine, extremely unlikely the Russians will try something like that in the next 50 days

Conflict has settled into a state suggesting a protracted conflict between Russia and Ukraine with no direct involvement from NATO countries. Only a black swan event would change this it seems. Possible but extremely unlikely in the next 3 months. Not 0% chance but closer to 0 than 1%.
All sides have shown respect for borders, containing the war to Ukrainian and Russian territory.

slightly reduceing because of the stalemate.
reduceing. The conflict is frozen at the Donbass region. Much further away from NATO border than it used to be.

and it worth reading this article by the FT

As the war intensifies and enters its “second phase”, Sweden & Finland are mulling joining NATO.
Nobody really knows what's going on with this war (any calculus will be wrong) - that in itself raises the possibility of lethal confrontation between NATO and Russia.

If the Russians suffer a humiliating defeat in the Donbas Putin will become more desperate. He may fire missiles at war materiel coming from NATO countries in an effort to dissuade the West from sending more heavy weapons to Ukraine. Some missiles may land in Ukraine, very near the Polish border; one could land on the Polish side of the border.
a very sensible possibility
It seems that there are not very many cool heads in Russia these days.
NATO doesn't want to kick the bear

Military engagement with a NATO member would initiate a regional conflagration which would include the involvement of an asymmetric response which could not be countered by Russia. This level of escalation would return Russia to international isolation along with a Soviet styled economy; it would also extend the duration of major power conflict into the future resulting in no off-ramps diplomatically or militarily.

It now appears Russia realizes that any focus on military operations in the area surrounding Kyiv and points to the West are much less likely than they were a month ago. https://www.understandingwar.org/backgrounder/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-april-4

Reducing my forecast a little because, at this point, it looks like Putin is beginning to (partially?) withdraw from Ukraine. This increases the chance of this conflict ending soon, and reduces the pressure for NATO intervention.
Updating forecast +2%: With Ukraine destroying oil infrastructure in Russia, this provides a reason for Russia to justify an escalation or delay peace talks

Current de-escalations, renewed peace talks, and gross incompetence by Russian military (+ significant losses) suggest Russian leaders may have lost appetite for continued actions or engaging NATO in direct confrontation.
Accidents are always a possibility, but right now Russian forces are super careful. They have enough troubles as is.

At the command levels, nobody wants this. Whether that will suffice to avoid accidents is always the big question, especially as the troops on the Russian side appear to be less well trained and disciplined. Still, as long as they stay inside Ukraine, Belarus and Russia, it probably won't happen.
Accidents happen. This many people with weapons, someone from NATO is bound to be hurt soon...

Russia, for all it's bluster, clearly knows that an attack on NATO would overwhelm its depleted forces. Furthermore, there are a number of NATO countries (namely Poland and Romania to a lesser extent) are as close to itching for a fight as possible in a country with cooler heads. Additionally, Russian forces are depleted enough that risking a confrontation by targeting a facility that's near the border of a NATO country but somehow overshooting is less likely because, it again knows it depleted, so it will give a several mile barrier. Finally, were Russia to target a NATO country, it would be with a missile, however, at least two Patriot missile defenses systems have been deployed to Eastern Poland [1] so, in the event of either a launch or errant missile, there would be an additional measure to mitigate any losses.
As opposed to a nonlethal confrontation resulting in 3 fatalities
Any killing of NATO uniforms will be done by Little Green Men. How this will be handled by the GJedi is up to them, but the Russian authorities will deny all knowledge and responsibility.
Combatants will want to avoid deliberate action, but the risk of accidental fratricide may be a factor
A lethal confrontation, whether planned or not, between national military forces as defined in the question. I don't believe the Russia's plan would be to extend action beyond the Ukraine.
Going up ahead of the NATO meeting next week and the ongoing possibility of Russia doing something that might provoke NATO further.

Russia has its hands full in Ukraine, so expanding the war would be a terrible idea, but there are a few unlikely events where could imagine it happening which justifies answering this question with 5%.

Several forecasters have also hit on this: there's always a chance of an accident; missed markings on a vehicle, or security detail at an infrastructure object not being aware of who is in the area, for example.
Fog of war.
This question is not clear.
I think Putin must realize this invasion isn't going anywhere. He's probably more concerned with damage control and saving face right now. Just a very shallow observation from me in this moment.

After some consideration I think my initial forecast (15%) is a bit low. Neither side wants a direct conflict, so we're essentially talking about the probability of a mistake of sufficient size being made, and that probability is fairly low day-by-day. But this goes on until either Putin withdraws from Ukraine, Zelenskyy surrenders, or a lasting ceasefire is agreed - and only the last of those three looks like it has any chance of happening imminently. If not, we keep rolling the dice each day, each week, each month, until sooner or later we get a bad result.
Accident is more likely than intention

Stoltenberg indicated today that NATO is still strongly against a no-fly zone, and presumably other direct interventions as well. Still, there is still the extraordinary meeting of Allied Heads of State and Government on the 24th, and something like the use of chemical weapons may change the balance.

My forecast of 5% is based on the possibility of a Russian mistake, which would happen because of its inability to precisely deliver weapons to targets. I believe they are compromised by Western electronic warfare and cyber warfare (happening through Ukrainian forces as proxies), hindering Russia's ability to see their aim points and target them. I don't think Russia wants to widen the war and draw in NATO, so I believe any lethal confrontation would be the result of a Russian tactical mistake.

Russia will test NATO
Russia either won't publicly admit to it, or else they'll place the blame on NATO.
The longer the invasion continues the greater the chances. I dont see an end to the conflict anytime soon therefore I think the odds are rising daily.

As Russian strikes extend further west, the risk to inadvertent damage, including loss of life (military or civilian) outside of UKR increases, see https://twitter.com/Reuters/status/1503146386279313415?s=20&t=tZcF073VLHlAE2u1dPNf7A and others following the attack on Yavoriv on Sunday, Mar 13th. This is true especially in Poland.

Russia have no reason to engage NATO forces and if they do it will likely be an accident. Joe Biden has made loud and obvious moves to bolster NATO defences and it’s clear NATO is serious about article 5.

Avoiding direct military conflict between NATO countries and Russia has been one of the guiding principles of Cold War and Post Cold War Era geopolitics. It is so engrained in the systems and minds of the security apparatus of both sides that I don't think we see a direct military conflict unless one of the sides believe they have no other choice.

The base rate here is relatively low. The reason why is because area of operations are delineated in very specific form with mistakes occurring being relatively rare. The Kremlin likely does not want escalation with NATO for no reason, nor does NATO want escalation with the Kremlin. What's left is the area of military mistakes - this space is not, to be sure, trivial, nor terribly small - but it is relatively small so as to avoid as much fatalities as can be predicted. Long story short: even if a single plane is shot down, moving up to 3 whole fatalities might be a relatively difficult thing to envision.

https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/06/us/politics/us-ukraine-weapons.html That article to me indicates a large amount of care is taken to avoid such a scenario. The US and Russia have many decades of confronting each other indirectly, and I would naturally expect that to continue. As for the Russian side, they seem bogged down enough in Ukraine right now that there's little chance they will expand the war elsewhere, such as invading the Baltic states.

As Russian forces move closer to the border of NATO states, the potential for miscalculation greatly increases. During the Ukraine campaign, Russian forces have proven to be more inept at targeting and precision weapons placement than anticipated. Alternatively, one or more NATO states could decide to engage Russian forces even if the conditions for Article 5 intervention are not met. In the increasingly likely event of the use of nuclear weapons, it will also be extremely difficult to predict the effects of nuclear blast/fallout on neighboring NATO states.

With Putin continuing minor provocations, war crimes and attempts to escalate the situation, I would imagine a not-impossible outcome where Russian forces miscalculate or deliberately take actions that result in deaths of NATO country authorities.
They're operating awfully close to Poland, but I think a China snub leads to a diplomatic solution soon.
6% chance not ONE mistake escalates to at least three bodies
One of two scenarios: Russia attacks military forces within a neighbouring NATO member country OR NATO forces enter Ukraine, Belarus or Russia to join the conflict and are killed.
Reconsidering my initial forecast, I think I underestimated Russia's ability to do something dumb based n what they've shown so far so I'm going up.
Accidents in this type of situation are likely to happen. And November 8 is a scaringly long time.
So many people engaged on avoiding this possibility but the war moving closer to the Poland border suggests that an accidental/ one-off incident is reasonably likely.

Attack on NATO vehicles & staff supplying weapons to Ukraine is most likely resulting in multiple deaths / will be claimed coincidental & collateral / will happen on Ukraine Territory. Also Russians might use their brain-destruction weapon on NATO pilots. But this requires short distance & direct visibility of a vehicle. They have already tried it on NATO pilots over Black Sea before this war

It seems like NATO is to act if any part of NATO is hit (https://fortune.com/2022/03/13/nato-will-act-russia-hits-alliance-us/) so the question is simply whether Russia will, intentionally or accidentally, hit NATO in one way or another. Intentionally seems unlikely. Without an indication of what a NATO response would be (i.e., whether it would be "proportionate" or not), this seems like a big risk for Russia, which is already taking big risks. It is, at the very least, clear that in a war involving NATO, Russia would have no chance given that they cannot even prevail against Ukraine. (Much credit due tot Ukraine, of course.) Accidentally seems more plausible because of how close Russian missiles are to hitting the Polish border (https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/mar/13/russia-widens-attacks-on-ukraine-with-missile-strike-on-base-close-to-polish-border) and previous recklessness in the black sea (now under more "control" due to Turkey, https://www.navalnews.com/naval-news/2022/02/turkey-closes-the-dardanelles-and-bosphorus-to-warships/). Still, this is not something that I would assign a high probability to.

This is difficult to predict. Both NATO and Russia want to avoid it, but tensions are high, Putin is hard to predict, and NATO is not quite one single voice either. I think the bar for establishing conflict on this question (three military fatalities) is quite low, and could potentially be reached by accident. If we decide to establish a no-fly zone that's also fairly likely to cause this many fatalities, even without further escalation.
FSB analyst have a demonstrated Russia's economic framework can only hold out until June

NATO members understand that a lethal confrontation between them and Russia might escalate to a nuclear war. So does Russia. It is therefore very unlikely that either parties will try and confront the other. there is a slight possibility of a unintended confrontation, due to Russia's invasion of Ukraine and weapons shipments to it.
This could happen on accident without leading to total war, despite apparently widespread belief that a single fatality will automatically lead to nuclear conflict.

If this happens it probably means full out war, so NATO at least will try to avoid it as far as possible. But we still can’t get a feel for where Putin is heading. And of course accidents happen. All it takes is someone to misdirect a weapon.
Not likely--- NATO doesn't want to anger the "bear".

I think neither side want this but that doesn't mean it won't happen. The likelihood of mistakes increases as the forces involved increase but I still think it's ultimately unlikely as NATO forces at least will try to mitigate against it happening.
This is one of those questions where I might as well go polar right from day 1. If the question resolves as ‘yes’, then shortly thereafter, who will be left to enjoy the brier score destruction?
